<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>WWW Business Applications Contest</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" content="WWW Business Innovations Contest- sponsored by Virginia's Center for Innovative Technology">
<META NAME="keywords" content="contest, awards, prizes, cash, Virginia, Business, java, competition, world wide web, WWW"></HEAD>

<BODY TEXT=#000000  LINK=#0000FF VLINK=#666666 BACKGROUND="./con-bg5.gif">

<CENTER>

<IMG BORDER=0 ALT="WWW Business Innovations Contest" SRC="contest.trans.gif">
<P>

</CENTER>


<P>
<B>

<A HREF="http://www.cit.org/">Virginia's Center for Innovative Technology (CIT)</A> and the <A HREF="http://intercom.virginia.edu/">Internet Commerce Group 
(InterCom)</A> are sponsoring a contest to develop World Wide Web concepts and 
applications that can benefit multiple companies in any of CIT's <A HREF="./indsectors.html">industry sectors</A>.  The 
goal of the contest is to create a collection of Web-based applications that will assist 
Virginia businesses in entering, promoting, utilizing, and profiting from the new paradigm 
of the <A HREF="./inetecon.html">Internet Economy</A>.  First prize is $5,000! 

</B>
<P>

CIT's mission is to enhance jobs, companies, and competitiveness (JCC) in Virginia.  This 
contest is your chance to participate in that mission.  Contest entries will identify (and 
ideally develop) a novel application of Web technology that would enhance a Virginia 
company's strategic position with regard to participation in the new <A HREF="./inetecon.html">Internet Economy</A>.  
Entries will define the new application, explain the need for it, identify the steps needed for 
implementation, and illustrate how a successful implementation would enhance JCC in 
Virginia.  Entrants will either develop a novel Web application or clearly identify one or 
more existing Web applications that could be modified to achieve the new concept.  
Entries must also identify at least five companies or entities in Virginia that could 
commercialize the new concept or technology. For some concept ideas, see <A HREF="./howto.html">How to Enter the Contest</A> for sample topics.
<P>
The judging criteria are:
<OL>
<LI>usefulness of the Web application to a broad spectrum of companies in any one of 
<A HREF="./indsectors.html">CIT's industry sectors</A>;
<LI>the application's potential for increasing jobs, companies, and competitiveness in 
Virginia; and
<LI>technical skill and elegance of the concept and its Web-based implementation.
</OL>
<P>

Contest entrants are restricted to full-time students at any of Virginia's two- and four-year 
colleges and universities.  Entries will be judged in two stages: a preliminary selection of 
15 "finalists," and then a final selection of the top five entries by industry leaders.  The top 
five prizes are scholarships of $5000, $4000, $3000, $2000, and $1000.  Winners will be 
recognized and prizes awarded at a public ceremony to be held at CIT's headquarters in 
Herndon, Virginia, in May 1997.
<P>


<P>
<CENTER>
<B>CONTEST SPONSORS</B>
<BR><A HREF="http://www.cit.org/">Virginia's Center for Innovative Technology (CIT)</A>
<BR><A HREF="http://intercom.virginia.edu/">The Internet Commerce Group (InterCom)</A>
</CENTER>

<P>
<CENTER>
<B>OTHER ORGANIZATIONS INVOLVED IN ELECTRONIC COMMERCE IN VIRGINIA</B>
<BR><A HREF="http://www.bev.net/">Blacksburg Electronic Village</A>
<BR><A HREF="http://knowledgeway.org/">Potomac KnowledgeWay</A>
<BR><A HREF="http://www.seva.net/">SEVAnet</A>
</CENTER>




<P>
