<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CIT Helps Create 2,013 Jobs and 103 Companies for Virginia</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#E6E8FA>

<H3>CIT Helps Create 2,013 Jobs and 103 Companies for Virginia</H3>
<B>Analysis Shows 90% of Three-year Goals Met in Two Years</B>
<P>
contact:
<BR>Debbie Barrigan:  (703) 689-3070
<BR>Alex Kozlov:  (703) 734-1880

<P>
Herndon, VA; October 23, 1996   Virginia's Center for Innovative Technology 
(CIT) announced that during FY96, it helped create, attract and retain 2013 
jobs and 103 companies, and helped create over $74 Million in increased 
competitiveness* for Virginia.  In addition, 94% of CIT clients said they 
would use CIT services again - a 3% increase over first-year results.  With 
these results, in two years CIT has reached almost 90% of its three-year 
goals for jobs and companies and has reached over 161% of its goal in 
competitiveness.
<P>
 These results reflect CIT's commitment to deliver tangible results to 
Virginia's technology-based businesses,  said Dr. Robert G. Templin, Jr., 
CIT's president.   The survey also enables us to develop programs and 
services that will continue to improve how we serve our clients in the 
future. 
<P>
Combined with FY95 results, CIT has assisted in the creation, attraction and 
retention of 5,571 jobs and 130 companies in Virginia, and has assisted in 
creating $161.7 Million in increased competitiveness* for Virginia.  The 
three-year goal (FY95 - FY97) is to assist in the creation, attraction, or 
retention of 6,000 jobs and 150 companies, and to increase company 
competitiveness by $100 Million.  These goals were established as a key 
component of CIT's strategic plan, approved by its Board of Directors in 
December 1994, that called for accountability - the establishment of clear, 
measurable goals or economic impact and the commitment to annual, independent 
client surveys to determine progress against the goals.
<P>
Conducted by The Institute of Public Policy at George Mason University 
(TIPP), the study collected data about activities for which the economic 
impact occurred during FY96.  The results came from nearly 400 CIT client 
companies.  The survey instrument was designed in 1995 by The Battelle Public 
Technology Program Office of the Battelle Memorial Institute and has been 
refined since then to reflect suggestions made during the first study.
<P>
The purpose of the survey was twofold:  to assess the impact of CIT's (and 
Partners) programs and services and to assess customer satisfaction in order 
to develop better programs and services. To obtain the economic impact that 
occurred in Fiscal Year 1996 (July 1, 1995 - June 30, 1996), it was necessary 
to contact FY96 customers as well as customers served during previous years, 
but whose results were achieved in FY96.  Based on the assumption that new 
technology usually takes four to seven years to enter the commercial market, 
customers that went as far back as seven years and no less than four years 
were included in the study.
<P>
A letter from the president and the survey instrument were sent to one 
representative in each company.  Data collection occurred over a three-month 
period.  The sum of the reported results of the past years  customers yielded 
the FY96 economic impact results.  Satisfaction metrics applied to FY96 only. 
<P>
<CITE>*competitiveness figure is based on a formula that includes public and 
private capital raised and increased sales.</CITE>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
