<HEAD>
<TITLE>CIT Industry Sector- Biotechnology and Medical</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../backgrounds/rib-bk2.gif">

<CENTER>
<H3><IMG SRC="../images/CIT.ribbon.tiny.trans.gif"> CIT Industry Sectors</H3>
<H1>Biotechnology and Medical</H1>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=0 HSPACE=8 SRC="./images/biotech.gif">
</CENTER>
<P>

The Biotech Industry in Virginia is young and extremely diverse, with 
distinct regional flavors.  Northern Virginia, particularly with the 
relocation of the <A HREF="http://atcc.org/">American Type Culture Collection (ATCC)</A> and its 
alliance with <A HREF="http://www.gmu.edu/~amoore2/pwi.html">GMU's Prince William Institute</A>, emphasizes Bioinformatics 
and companies involved in the Human Genome project.  Central Virginia and 
the Richmond Area are home to companies developing human diagnostics and 
therapeutics.  The <A HREF="http://views.vcu.edu/html/biomede/vbrp.html">Biotechnology Park</A> and CIT's Drug Development 
Canter at <A HREF="http://www.vcu.edu/">VCU</A> underscore this theme.  The <A HREF="http://www.virginia.edu/">University of Virginia</A> 
in Charlottesville has spun out companies working in the area of 
Medical imaging and Telemedicine as well as working with &#34;Defense 
Conversion&#34; companies from Northern Virginia.  Southern Virginia 
emphasizes agricultural biotechnology, including companies involved 
in Transgenic plants and animals.

<P>
The Biotechnology program is working with groups like the Virginia 
Biotechnology Association (VBAS) and the Williamsburg Bioprocessing 
Foundation to create an atmosphere conducive to the growth of this 
young industry. In June, the Program awarded Industry Development awards 
to the ATCC/GMU alliance and the Virginia Health Informatics Institute at 
UVA specifically targeting new efforts in economic development.  The 
Program is currently negotiating with the Greater Richmond Partnership 
about how CIT can work with their Virginia company retention program as 
well as assist VCU in locating companies to the <A HREF="http://views.vcu.edu/html/biomede/vbrp.html">Biotech Park</A>.  In 
partnership with VBA, the program is publishing a fall directory of 
Biotechnology companies and resources and planning events at <A HREF="http://www.gmu.edu/">GMU</A>, <A HREF="http://www.vt.edu/">VA 
Tech</A>, and the opening of the <A HREF="http://views.vcu.edu/html/biomede/vbrp.html">Biotech Park</A>.  In November, CIT is 
sponsoring a conference on &#34 Viral Vectors and Vaccines &#34 with 
the Williamsburg Bioprocessing Foundation.

<P>
The CIT Biotechnology and Medical Industry Director is 
<A HREF="../people/rschwartz.html">Robert M. Schwartz</A>.  
For more information regarding this industry, please call him at 
(703) 689-3027 or send an e-mail to:  
<A HREF="mailto:bobs@cit.org">bobs@cit.org</A>.

<P>
For a list of Virginia companies in this industry sector, take a look
at the <A HREF="http://intercom.virginia.edu/cgi-bin/vtr-tech-query?Biotechnology+and+Biomedical+Applications"><B>Biotechnology and Biomedical Applications section</B></A> of the <A HREF="../VA.technology.html">Virginia Technology Resources (VTR)</A> list.

<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

&#160;<P>
Other potentially helpful links:<BR>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.bio.com/">Bio Online: Biotechnology on the 'Net</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://views.vcu.edu/html/biomede/vbrp.html">Virginia Biotechnology Research Park</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.bigyellow.com/">BigYellow</A> internet yellow pages
<LI><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Science/Biology/Biotechnology/">Yahoo's Biotechnology index</A>

</UL>

<CENTER>
